1
00:00:03,031 --> 00:00:05,843
In 1912, fragments from a gravel pit

2
00:00:05,843 --> 00:00:08,655
in Sussex seemed to give British science

3
00:00:08,655 --> 00:00:11,466
the fossil it wanted, a human-like skull,

4
00:00:11,466 --> 00:00:14,278
an ape-like jaw, a famous name Piltdown

5
00:00:14,278 --> 00:00:17,090
Man.

6
00:00:18,201 --> 00:00:19,643
The evidence was thin, but the story

7
00:00:19,643 --> 00:00:21,085
was powerful.

8
00:00:22,167 --> 00:00:24,381
It fit a brain-first theory and gave

9
00:00:24,381 --> 00:00:26,594
Britain its own ancient ancestor.

10
00:00:27,435 --> 00:00:29,844
Some anatomists doubted the skull and jaw

11
00:00:29,844 --> 00:00:32,252
belonged together, but access was limited, prestige

12
00:00:32,252 --> 00:00:34,661
was heavy, and the specimen kept circulating

13
00:00:34,661 --> 00:00:37,070
as authority.

14
00:00:37,771 --> 00:00:39,033
The fraud was not perfect.

15
00:00:39,774 --> 00:00:40,435
It was welcome.

16
00:00:41,417 --> 00:00:45,323
By 1953, tests exposed the trick.

17
00:00:45,302 --> 00:00:47,189
The skull was recent human bone.

18
00:00:47,993 --> 00:00:49,537
The jaw was from an orangutan.

19
00:00:50,200 --> 00:00:51,505
The teeth had been filed.

20
00:00:52,106 --> 00:00:53,392
The bones had been stained.

21
00:00:54,113 --> 00:00:55,739
The hoax survived because it let the

22
00:00:55,739 --> 00:00:57,365
field feel correct.

23
00:00:58,289 --> 00:00:59,805
The mystery fades.

24
00:00:59,805 --> 00:01:01,320
The receipts remain.
